%U A393665 1874038107800370,26527162393038300,378160443213077840,5424985742151048640,78266294077222701884,1134914052039617826556
%N A393665 Number of order-convex subsets of the square grid poset [n]^2 with componentwise partial order.
%C A393665 A subset S of [n]^2 = {1,...,n}^2 with componentwise order is order-convex if whenever a, b in S with a <= c <= b, then c in S. Equivalently, S is the intersection of a downset and an upset.
%C A393665 The growth constant rho = lim a(n)^(1/n) = 16. The upper bound rho <= 16 follows from an ideal/filter injection a(n) <= C(2n,n)^2; the lower bound follows from a tiling argument. Both bounds are formally verified in Lean 4.
%C A393665 The sequence is supermultiplicative: a(m+n) >= a(m)*a(n) for all m, n >= 1.
%C A393665 Barnette, Nichols, and Richmond (2019) gave exact formulas for the number of order-convex subsets of [n] x [m] for small fixed m. The present sequence counts order-convex subsets of the square grid [n]^2 as a function of n.
%C A393665 a(n) can be computed by a transfer-matrix method with C(n+2,2) states.
%D A393665 B. Barnette, W. Nichols, and T. Richmond, The number of convex sets in a product of totally ordered sets, Rocky Mountain J. Math., 49 (2019), no. 2, 369-385.
%H A393665 Thomas DiFiore, <a href="https://github.com/tomdif/causal-algebraic-geometry-lean">Lean 4 formal verification</a>.
%H A393665 Thomas DiFiore, <a href="https://zenodo.org/records/19271288">Causal-Algebraic Geometry</a>, Zenodo.
%H A393665 B. Barnette, W. Nichols, and T. Richmond, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1216/RMJ-2019-49-2-369">The number of convex sets in a product of totally ordered sets</a>, Rocky Mountain J. Math. 49(2): 369-385 (2019).
%F A393665 a(m+n) >= a(m)*a(n) for all m, n >= 1 .
%F A393665 a(n) <= C(2n,n)^2 <= 16^n.
%F A393665 Limit_{n->oo} a(n)^(1/n) = 16.
%e A393665 a(1) = 2: the empty set and {(1,1)}.
%e A393665 a(2) = 13: the empty set, 4 singletons, 4 edges (pairs of comparable elements), 3 triples (L-shapes and the diagonal), and the full grid.
%o A393665 (Python)
%o A393665 # Brute force for small n; use transfer matrix for n > 4
%o A393665 from itertools import product, combinations
%o A393665 def is_convex(S, n):
%o A393665     S = set(S)
%o A393665     for a in S:
%o A393665         for b in S:
%o A393665             if a[0]<=b[0] and a[1]<=b[1]:
%o A393665                 for c in product(range(a[0],b[0]+1), range(a[1],b[1]+1)):
%o A393665                     if c not in S: return False
%o A393665     return True
%o A393665 def a(n):
%o A393665     grid = list(product(range(n), repeat=2))
%o A393665     count = 0
%o A393665     for r in range(len(grid)+1):
%o A393665         for S in combinations(grid, r):
%o A393665             if is_convex(S, n): count += 1
%o A393665     return count
%o A393665 print([a(n) for n in range(1, 5)])  # [2, 13, 114, 1146]
%Y A393665 Cf. A394682.
%K A393665 nonn
%O A393665 1,1
